New Hope for India
Cambridge, USA — India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and leader of the Congress Party, has been ruling behind the scenes since 1998, while Singh has been little more than a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued populist agendas and increased transfer payments, leading to India's annual economic growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised rapid job and income growth for all of India, just as he did when he was Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with expanded economic activity and attracting commercial investments from both within and outside India.
A key feature of the latest election was that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which is arguably an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
The two key officials will support Modi in his economic plans.
The newly appointed Finance Minister, Arun Jaitley, has extensive political experience and served as a minister in the previous BJP government.
Jaitely is also renowned as a strategist who is sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as Governor, he expressed a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to address some inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth take time to be implemented and produce results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has world-class higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities they provide, because primary and secondary education in India is highly underdeveloped.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy skills at the primary school level.
Teachers themselves have poor educational backgrounds and lack motivation, with many never even appearing at their schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
Recent expansion of private airlines and airports shows that private enterprises can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal consolidation.
Large budget deficits are absorbing national savings that could otherwise be used to expand commercial investment. Budget deficits have led to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxation.
Privatization.
State-owned manufacturing and other industries in the Indian government operate inefficiently and often result in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Subsidies for electricity and energy lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, due to an impressive new system of cash transfers based on fingerprint technology, India's cash transfer program is highly efficient.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is a large stockpiling of goods in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and regional zoning.
As long as you have visited Mumbai or other major Indian cities, you will see that regional zoning restrictions lead to inefficient land use in urban areas, constraining development.
Unclear property rights, especially agricultural land rights, prevent industrialization in rural areas.
Relax foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign companies cannot be majority shareholders in banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
The complex system of central and state-level sales taxes in India distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a fiscal decentralization model has been ongoing for a long time, and it is now time to move to implementation.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases undermine economic confidence and hinder officials' decision-making.
India is also plagued by petty corruption, with bribery having become a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and curb petty corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by strong growth and expectations of increased profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to show the world that they can fulfill their campaign promises.
